        <p style="color:white">
   Indian greetings are deeply rooted in the cultural practice of Añjali Mudrā, including Pranāma and Puja. Common greetings include Namaste (Hindi, Sanskrit, and Kannada), Namaskar (Marathi), Namaskara (Kannada and Sanskrit), Paranaam (Bhojpuri), Namaskaram (Telugu, Malayalam), Vanakkam (Tamil), Nômôshkar (Bengali), Nomoskar (Assamese), Aadab (Urdu), and Sat Shri Akal (Punjabi). These salutations, used both when meeting and departing, express deep respect. Namaskar is considered slightly more formal than Namaste, both derived from the Sanskrit words "Namah" (to bow) and "te" (to you), meaning "I bow to you." In Hinduism, it signifies "I bow to the divine in you."

Other traditional greetings include Jai Jagannath (Odia), Ami Aschi (Bengali), Jai Shri Krishna (Gujarati and Braj Bhasha/Rajasthani), Ram Ram or Jai Sita Ram ji (Awadhi and Bhojpuri), As-salamu alaykum (Urdu), Jai Jinendra (Jainism), Jai Bhim (Ambedkarism), Namo Buddhay (Buddhism), Allah Abho (Baháʼí Faith), Shalom aleichem (Judaism), Hamazor Hama Ashobed (Zoroastrianism), Sahebji (Parsi), Dorood (Irani), Om Namah Shivaya/Jai Bholenath Jaidev (Dogri, Kashmiri, Varanasi), Jai Ambe Maa/Jai Mata di (Eastern India), and Jai Ganapati Bapa (Marathi, Konkani). In business and urban settings, a handshake is more common, replacing traditional greetings.
